Commentary: hints of swing into him as Guptill keeps his front pad out of the way and blocks to mid-on

Commentary: ooooh, he really is feeling it! Only a man in form can hit a cover drive on the up first ball. This is a superb over from Shaheen and he hasn't done much wrong with this ball either, pitching it up and across the right-hander. But Seifert is so in control of his game, so confident, that he presses forward strongly and drills it between mid-off and cover

Commentary: good length and cutting back into the right-hander, immediately denying him the room that he relished in so recently. Seifert defends
Commentary_short: Shaheen Shah Afridi to Seifert, no run

Commentary: misfield at cover. It's Hafeez there, who ends up overrunning the ball, which was short and outside off and got a Guptill punch for its troubles

Commentary: keeps to his crease against a fullish delivery on leg stump and blocks
Commentary_short: Mohammad Hasnain to Seifert, no run

Commentary: flashes at it and comes up with nothing! This is neither a cross-bat shot, nor a straight bat punch. He simply wants to force a short ball through the off side and it doesn't happen for him

Commentary: blocks a back of a length ball on middle
Commentary_short: Mohammad Hasnain to Seifert, no run

Commentary: he's McCullum-ed it! He has absolutely McCullum-ed it! That man absolutely loved charging at 150 kph fast bowlers and tonking them over the top of the off side. And his protege is following suit. Sensational shot over point.

Commentary: that shot inspires a little extra venom from Hasnain, running in harder, hitting the deck better, and he gets extra bounce to beat a tame cut shot attempt

Commentary: takes on the short ball on leg stump and pulls it sweetly to deep square leg

Commentary: he lofts it, but he hasn't quite timed it. Comes possibly off the bottom of the bat as he goes after a full ball on middle and mid-on catches up with it fairly easily

Commentary: defends a good length ball on off stump
Commentary_short: Shaheen Shah Afridi to Guptill, no run

Commentary: top edge but it sails away! Poor poor Afridi. He watches yet another good ball go to the boundary. Makes this climb up to the batsman's throat, but the instinctive hook from Guptill returns a profit

Commentary: works it to deep square leg

Commentary: good length ball outside off, Guptill is looking to smash it down the ground, it sneaks under his bat

Commentary: shortish and into the body, cramps Guptill up as he tries to flick it through midwicket. He's too slow on the shot
Commentary_short: Mohammad Hasnain to Guptill, no run

Commentary: oh that's clever! He's probably been waiting for that. He knows the bowlers are trying to tuck him up. He's seen fine leg up inside the circle. This short ball is a bit too leg side and so immediately he whips it away to the fine leg boundary. Good batting

Commentary: turns a short of a length delivery on off stump to deep square leg

Commentary: thumps it down the ground. This is a baseball biff! The front leg is lost. It's gone. It's out of the way. It doesn't matter. It's all about hand-eye here. A short ball outside off - it's well above the waist and climbing - yet Seifert is able to get right on top of it and launch it over the bowler's head. Special hitting

Commentary: full on off stump, works it to mid-on
Commentary_short: Haris Rauf to Guptill, no run

Commentary: inside out and down the ground. He really is monstrous the moment he can go down the ground. He makes that possible against this full ball on leg stump by staying beside it and then it's all about that big, powerful bat swing. Guptill has definitely hit form!

Commentary: taken at mid-off. Tries to recreate the magic from the last ball. Tries to pull off that inside out loft down the ground again. But two things are amiss. One, the length is shorter. Commentary: punches a short of a length ball on off stump to cover

Commentary: past mid-on. It's a tough stop. But Seifert didn't quite time it as well as he could have. He definitely wants to drill this down the ground, but it comes off the bat a little higher than he would like. Shaheen is the fielder needing to dive to his left, and he lets it through

Commentary: stands tall and punches a short of a length ball outside off to point
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Williamson, no run

Commentary: chops on! That's happened a few times before. It's short. It's wide. And oddly enough, his footwork, moving back and across, works against him here because he gets too close to the ball and ends up reducing the room he had to cut the ball. That little reduction is enough to secure the inside edge onto his stumps. Williamson hunches over his bat and stares at the pitch as if it's betrayed him. Maybe he thought that ball would come onto the bat more, bounce more?
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Williamson, OUT
Dismissal_text: KS Williamson  b Faheem Ashraf 1 (6m 4b 0x4 0x6) SR: 25.00

Commentary: beats him outside off as he comes around the wicket and gets a shortish ball to straighten past the left-hander.
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Conway, no run

Commentary: defends a fuller ball into the covers to get off the mark
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Conway, 1 run

Commentary: stays back and turns a shortish delivery on middle towards mid-on
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Seifert, 1 run

Commentary: lovely start as he gets a legbreak to drift into middle and turn just enough to keep Seifert honest
Commentary_short: Shadab Khan to Seifert, no run

Commentary: top edge.... and it carries all the way over square leg! Seifert is reaching for this. He's premeditated the sweep, allowing Shadab to hold the ball back and angle it wider outside off. And yet Seifert comes out the winner. Man, these big fat bats!

Commentary: rocks back and cuts the flatter delivery outside off to the sweeper
Commentary_short: Shadab Khan to Seifert, 1 run

Commentary: nudges a good length ball on off stump to deep midwicket
Commentary_short: Shadab Khan to Conway, 1 run

Commentary: dabs a shortish ball outside off to point
Commentary_short: Shadab Khan to Seifert, no run

Commentary: shifts leg side of the tossed up ball on middle and lifts it to long-off. The fielder didn't see it clearly with the sun in his eyes. Not a catching chance though and he recovers well enough.

Commentary: whip drive, those wrists putting power into the full ball outside off, and finding a single at deep point
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Conway, 1 run

Commentary: knocks him out! Oh this is lovely bowling. It's the magic of the wobble seam. You don't let it stay upright. You make it dance as the ball comes out. And when it pitches on the surface, it does whatever it pleases. Here, it decks in off a good length, cuts Seifert in half, and takes out his off stump. The on-the-up drive was the worst shot he could play given the trap that was being set. Ashraf has been brilliant today!
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Seifert, OUT
Dismissal_text: TL Seifert  b Faheem Ashraf 35 (36m 20b 2x4 3x6) SR: 175.00

Commentary: defends a full ball on off stump
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Phillips, no run

Commentary: inside edge and almost onto the stumps! Ashraf's wobble seam ball is creating mayhem! He keeps targeting the top of off stump. He doesn't let the batsman cut or pull. He may tempt them on the drive, but like Seifert, they'll be doing that at their peril. Here, since Phillips is still new at the crease, he is on the back foot trying to punch the ball through the covers. Instead, he gets a single to fine leg

Commentary: full and outside off, smashes it through the covers
Commentary_short: Faheem Ashraf to Conway, 1 run

Commentary: clips a good length ball on off stump to the right of mid-on

Commentary: beats him with an invitingly tossed up legbreak outside off. Oh, Pakistan are feeling it!

Commentary: slices to point, but there's no run there, oh wait, the fielder's throw is so far to the keeper's right that it becomes an overthrow

Commentary: full and on middle, he drives inside out through the covers
Commentary_short: Shadab Khan to Conway, 1 run

Commentary: fiiiiiiierrrrrrce strike as he charges out of his crease again and isn't perturbed by the bowler going short to confuse him. Commentary: steers the back of a length ball - he's back around the wicket to cramp the left-hander and deny him off-side shots - to third man

Commentary: pushes a back of a length ball outside off down the pitch

Commentary: pulls a short ball out to deep square leg

Commentary: tipped to short fine leg, and they scamper a single

Commentary: drives it back to the bowler, who's alert enough to ensure a single isn't stolen

Commentary: targets the batsman's hips, whose swivel-pull couldn't quite connect

Commentary: driven down the ground and hit's the non-striker's stumps

Commentary: poked into the offside and they exchange ends

Commentary: pushes him onto the backfoot, Conway eases that through the covers

Commentary: keeps the strike with a little dab down the onside

Commentary: gets off strike with a dabble to mid-on

Commentary: dropped but boy, was that ever hit hard. Haider has put everything into the shot. It's flying to Guptill. He sees it well. Moves to his right with both hands. The ball flicks the fingertips and slips off into the covers
Commentary_short: Kuggeleijn to Haider Ali, 2 runs

Commentary: that is a ripppaaaahhhhhhh! A one-handed rippppaaaahhhhhh! Guptill had just stepped away to take care of those fingers that must be burning right now. Daryl Mitchell came in as a sub and immediately he has pulled off the impossible. A back of a length ball that stops on the pitch gets a leading edge as Haider, who plays with hard hands, who succeeds with hard hands, here watches the ball spoon over the off side infield. He might think he's got enough on it to beat the man tracking back. But Mitchell keeps his eye on it as he runs sideways and back from cover, then propels himself further with an acrobatic dive and finally thrusts his right hand up and behind him and it sticks. IT STICKS!
Commentary_short: Kuggeleijn to Haider Ali, OUT
Dismissal_text: Haider Ali c sub (DJ Mitchell) b Kuggeleijn 11 (25m 9b 1x4 0x6) SR: 122.22
